    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-18T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-18T17:00:00-05:00" n="137"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d137">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5017/11–1844: Circular telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Certain <gloss type="to">Diplomatic Representatives in the American
                            Republics</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="37" xml:id="d137fn37">Sent to Brazil, Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, El
                        Salvador, Honduras Nicaragua, Peru, and Venezuela.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-18T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >November 18, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The decision announced by the OPA<note n="38" xml:id="d137fn38">Office of Price
                        Administration.</note> and WFA<note n="39" xml:id="d137fn39">War Food
                        Administration.</note> on November 15 to deny the petition of the
                    Inter-American Coffee Board to the OPA for an increase in the coffee ceiling
                    price was reached after Byrnes<note n="40" xml:id="d137fn40">James F. Byrnes,
                        Director of War Mobilization.</note> met with Vinson,<note n="41"
                        xml:id="d137fn41">Fred M. Vinson, Director, Office of Economic
                        Stabilization.</note> Marvin Jones,<note n="42" xml:id="d137fn42"
                        >Administrator of the War Food Administration.</note> Bowles,<note n="43"
                        xml:id="d137fn43">Chester Bowles, Administrator, Office of Price
                        Administration.</note> other officials <pb facs="0179" n="165"
                        xml:id="pg_165"/> of WFA and OPA and two officers of the Department. The
                    decision was based very largely on domestic factors, such as the necessity for
                    holding the price line, for holding down the cost of living and maintaining
                    wages at their present levels in conformity with the Little Steel formula.</p>
                <p>The Inter-American Coffee Board which met November 16 took the decision very hard
                    and issued a press release stating their surprise at the decision and adding the
                    following sentence “The Board is considering at this time a reply to the Office
                    of Price Administration and will continue to take whatever steps are necessary
                    to maintain the flow of coffee to the United States market while this matter is
                    pending”. It is highly improbable that any relief action will be taken by the
                    OPA.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
